erg','Real economic growth continued to be strong in 2005, mainly reflecting strong growth in the services-producing sector. Thirty-one of the thirty-six services-producing industries expanded in 2005. The goods sector also expanded in 2005.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2006/12december/1206_indyaccts.pdf','Industry, Industry accounts','2006-12-15',NULL,'Tables','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2006/12december/1206_indyaccts_tables.pdf','Domestic Supply and Use of Oil and Gas Extraction and Petroleum and Coal Products','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2006/12december/1206_indyaccts.pdf#page=4',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-86-12-07',86,12,'December',2006,'Subject Guide for 2006',NULL,'This guide lists the articles that were published in the Survey in 2006.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2006/12december/1206_subjguide.pdf',NULL,'2006-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-86-12-08',86,12,'December',2006,'Schedule of News Release in 2007',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/newsreleases/general/pdf/2007rd.pdf',NULL,'2006-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-01',85,1,'January',2005,'Business Situation: Final Estimates for the Third Quarter of 2004','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan','Economic growth picked up in the third quarter. Real GDP increased 4.0 percent after increasing 3.3 percent in the second quarter; the pickup mainly reflected a step-up in consumer spending. Inflation slowed; the price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.9 percent after increasing 3.5 percent. Real disposable personal income slowed, increasing 2.0 percent after increasing 2.8 percent. Corporate profits decreased $55.9 billion (4.8 percent at a quarterly rate) after increasing $8.3 billion. The decrease mainly reflected a decrease in the profits of financial corporations.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105bsf.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-01-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-02',85,1,'January',2005,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade for the Third Quarter of 2004',NULL,'The estimates have been updated, including the estimates of inventories for manufacturing by stage of fabrication.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105_ISR.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2005-01-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-03',85,1,'January',2005,'Annual Industry Accounts: Revised Estimates for 2001-2003','George M. Smith, Matthew J. Gruenberg, Tameka R.L. Harris, Erich H. Strassner','These revised, more detailed estimates of the integrated annual GDP-by-industry accounts and the input-output accounts present an updated picture of U.S. economic activity that confirms and clarifies the industry trends that were indicated by the previously published estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105_Industry_Acct.pdf','Industry, Industry accounts','2005-01-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-04',85,1,'January',2005,'U.S. International Transactions: Third Quarter of 2004','Douglas B. Weinberg, Kelly K. Pierce','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $0.3 billion to $164.7 billion. The slight increase was accounted for by a $3.2 billion increase in the deficit on goods, reflecting a larger increase in imports than in exports, and by a $1.1 billion decrease in the surplus on services. In contrast, net outflows for unilateral current transfers decreased $3.7 billion, and the surplus on income increased $0.2 billion. In the financial account, net recorded financial inflows decreased $11.7 billion. Both outflows for U.S.-owned assets abroad and inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States increased, but outflows increased more than inflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105_ITA.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2005-01-21',NULL,'Interactive Data','http://bea.gov/international/bp_web/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-05',85,1,'January',2005,'An Ownership-Based Framework of the U.S. Current Account, 1992-2003','Jeffrey H. Lowe','BEA\'s ownership-based current account has been updated. This report presents revised estimates for 1992-2002 and new summary estimates for 2003. This framework supplements BEA\'s international transactions accounts by highlighting the participation of multinational companies in the international markets for goods and services through both cross-border trade and sales by local affiliates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/Current-Acct.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2005-01-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-06',85,1,'January',2005,'Comprehensive Revision of Gross State Product: Accelerated Estimates for 2003 and Revised Estimates for 1977-2002','Gerard P. Aman, George K. Downey, Sharon D. Panek','This revision incorporates the results of the comprehensive revisions of the NIPAs, of the annual integrated industry accounts, and of the state personal income accounts. As a result, BEA\'s regional accounts are now more consistent with the estimates of GDP and GDP by industry. This revision also features the accelerated release of current-dollar estimates of GSP for 2003.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105_GSP.pdf','Regional, Gross state product','2005-01-21',NULL,'Interactive Data','http://bea.gov/iTable/index_regional.cfm',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-01-07',85,1,'January',2005,'State Personal Income: Third Quarter of 2004','David G. Lenze','Personal income growth for the Nation slowed to a 0.8-percent increase from a 1.6-percent increase in the second quarter. Personal income growth in all but seven states slowed. Hurricane property damage affected personal income growth in Florida and Alabama. Earnings growth was concentrated in seven industries. In several states with large farm sectors, the slow growth in personal income reflected decreases in farm earnings.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/01January/0105_SPI.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2005-01-21',NULL,'Interactive Data','http://bea.gov/iTable/index_regional.cfm',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-02-01',85,2,'February',2005,'Business Situation: Advance Estimates for the Fourth Quarter of 2004 and for 2004','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan','Economic growth slowed in the fourth quarter. Real GDP increased 3.1 percent after increasing 4.0 percent in the third quarter; the slowdown mainly reflected an increase in the trade deficit and a slowdown in consumer spending for durable goods. Inflation picked up: The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.7 percent after increasing 1.9 percent, mainly reflecting an acceleration in energy prices. Real disposable personal income surged, increasing 8.4 percent after increasing 2.0 percent. In 2004, real GDP increased 4.4 percent after increasing 3.0 percent in 2003. The acceleration reflected accelerations in nonresidential fixed investment, in exports, and in consumer spending and an upturn in inventory investment. Inflation remained moderate.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/02February/0205_BSA.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-02-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-02-02',85,2,'February',2005,'Reliability of the NIPA Estimates of U.S. Economic Activity','Dennis J. Fixler, Bruce T. Grimm','The results of the most recent review of the estimates of GDP and of gross domestic income confirm that these estimates continue to present an accurate picture of U.S. economic activity. Specifically, the quarterly estimates reliably indicate whether U.S. economic growth is contracting or expanding and whether it is accelerating or decelerating. The estimates also accurately show current economic growth and the long-term trends in growth.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/02February/0205_NIPAs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-02-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-02-03',85,2,'February',2005,'Hedonic Price Indexes for Digital Cameras','Kari Manninen','This research tested five methods of adjustment to account for differences in the quality of digital cameras. All five methods produced similar results. These results suggest that simple, hedonic price indexes may be used to accurately control for the quality of products with rapidly changing features, such as digital cameras, and to reliably supplement the more conventional matched-model methods.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/02February/0205_Digital.pdf','Research Spotlight','2005-02-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-03-01',85,3,'March',2005,'Business Situation: Preliminary Estimates for the Fourth Quarter of 2004','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan','Economic growth slowed slightly in the fourth quarter. Real GDP increased 3.8 percent after increasing 4.0 percent in the third quarter. The slowdown mainly reflected an acceleration in the trade deficit and a slowdown in consumer spending for durable goods; inventory investment turned up. Inflation picked up: The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.8 percent after increasing 1.9 percent, mainly reflecting an acceleration in energy prices. Real disposable personal income surged, increasing 8.1 percent after increasing 2.9 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/03March/0305bsp.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-03-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-03-02',85,3,'March',2005,'Federal Budget Estimates for Fiscal Year 2006','Michelle D. Robinson, Benjamin A. Mandel','Each year, BEA adjusts the Federal budget estimates of receipts and outlays from the Budget of the United States Government so that these estimates are consistent with the NIPAs. The adjusted estimates are then used to prepare quarterly estimates of Federal Government current receipts and current expenditures. For fiscal year 2006, net Federal Government saving is projected to be -$392.5 billion; the Federal budget projects a deficit of $390.1 billion. Federal Government current receipts are projected to increase $136.2 billion; Federal budget receipts are projected to increase $124.7 billion. Federal Government current expenditures are projected to increase $126.1 billion; Federal budget outlays are projected to increase $88.2 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/03March/0305_FedBudget.pdf','National, Federal budget estimates','2005-03-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-04-01',85,4,'April',2005,'Business Situation: Final Estimates for the Fourth Quarter of 2004','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan, Christopher Falcone','Economic growth slowed slightly in the fourth quarter. Real GDP increased 3.8 percent after increasing 4.0 percent in the third quarter. The slowdown mainly reflected an acceleration in imports and a deceleration in consumer spending; inventory investment turned up. Inflation picked up: The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.9 percent after increasing 1.9 percent, mainly reflecting an acceleration in energy prices. Corporate profits increased $150.8 billion (13.5 percent at a quarterly rate) after decreasing $55.9 billion, reflecting an increase in the profits of domestic corporations. Net government saving was -$320.6 billion, increasing $49.9 billion from -$370.5 billion. Net Federal Government saving was -$356.2 billion, increasing $18.8 billion from -$375 billion. Net state and local government saving was $35.6 billion, increasing $31.1 billion from $4.5 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/BSF.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-04-19',NULL,'Saving, Wealth, Investment, and the Current-Account Deficit','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/BSFbox.pdf#page=3',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-04-02',85,4,'April',2005,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade for the Fourth Quarter of 2004',NULL,'The estimates have been updated, including the estimates of inventories for manufacturing by stage of fabrication.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/ISR.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2005-04-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-04-03',85,4,'April',2005,'U.S. International Transactions: Fourth Quarter of 2004','Renee M. Sauers, Kelly K. Pierce','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $22.0 billion, to $187.9 billion. The increase was mainly accounted for by a $16.5 billion increase in the deficit on goods, reflecting a substantial pickup in imports and a slowdown in exports. Net outflows for unilateral current transfers increased $4.1 billion, and the surplus on income decreased $2.8 billion. The surplus on services increased $1.3 billion. In the financial account, net recorded financial inflows increased $55.1 billion. Both outflows for U.S.-owned assets abroad and inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States increased, but inflows increased more than outflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/ITAQ.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2005-04-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-04-04',85,4,'April',2005,'U.S. International Transactions, 2004','Christopher L. Bach','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $135.3 billion, to $665.9 billion in 2004. The increase was mainly accounted for by a $117.9 billion increase in the deficit on goods. The surplus on income decreased $9.2 billion, net outflows for unilateral current transfers increased $5.5 billion, and the surplus on services decreased $2.6 billion. In the financial account, net recorded financial inflows increased $69.7 billion, to $615.5 billion, as financial inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States increased more than financial outflows for U.S.-owned assets abroad.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/ITA.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2005-04-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-04-05',85,4,'April',2005,'State Personal Income for the Fourth Quarter of 2004 and State Per Capita Personal Income for 2004','David G. Lenze','Personal income growth for the Nation surged to a 2.6-percent increase from a 1.1-percent increase in the third quarter. The surge mainly reflected a special dividend by Microsoft Corporation, but earnings growth in three other industries also contributed. Personal income growth in all but one state accelerated. The pace of per capita personal income for the Nation in 2004 picked up to a 4.7-percent increase after increasing 2.2 percent in 2003. Per capita personal income growth in all but three states accelerated. The growth was affected by the Microsoft dividend, by unusually high farm prices and production, and by payments by automakers to reduce their unfunded pension liabilities in 2003.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/SPI.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2005-04-19',NULL,'Alternative Measures of Household Income','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/04April/SPIbox.pdf#page=7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-05-01',85,5,'May',2005,'Business Situation: Advance Estimates for the First Quarter of 2005','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan','Real GDP grew 3.1 percent in the first quarter of 2005, compared with 3.8 percent in the preceding quarter. The lower growth rate reflected a slowdown in business investment in equipment and software, a slowdown in consumer spending, and a widening of the trade balance.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/05May/0505BSA.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2005-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-05-02',85,5,'May',2005,'Annual Industry Accounts: Advance Estimates for 2004','Brian C. Moyer, Shelly Smith, David F. Sullivan','The U.S. economy in 2004 reflected robust growth in the private services-producing sector, moderate growth in the goods-producing sector, and a modest acceleration in prices.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/05May/IndyAccts_ArticleB%26W.pdf','Industry, Industry accounts','2005-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-85-05-03',85,5,'May',2005,'Local Area Personal Income for 2001-2003','David G. Lenze','Growth in local area personal income accelerated in 2003. Personal income in micropolitan areas grew 3.7 percent, and personal income in metropolitan areas grew 3.1 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2005/05May/0505lapimain.pdf','Reg