NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-02',81,10,'October',2001,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Dan Larkins','Real GDP edged up 0.3 percent in the second quarter of 2001, according to the \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 0.2-percent increase. The largest revision was a downward revision to imports of services, which are subtracted in the calculation of GDP. The \"revised\" estimate of corporate profits showed a decrease of $30.0 billion (3.8 percent at a quarterly rate); the \"preliminary\" estimate had shown a decrease of $28.5 billion (3.6 percent).','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001BSF.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-10-16',NULL,'Tables 1 through 5','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001bs1-5.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-03',81,10,'October',2001,'U.S. International Transactions, Second Quarter 2001','Douglas B. Weinberg','The U.S. current-account deficit decreased $5.3 billion, to $106.5 billion, in the second quarter of 2001. A decrease in the deficit on goods and an increase in the surplus on services more than offset increases in the deficit on income and in net outflows for unilateral current transfers. In the financial account, net recorded inflows increased $21.2 billion, to $124.7 billion, as financial inflows decreased less than financial outflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001itaq.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2001-10-16',NULL,'Tables A through E','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001itaqA-D.xls','Spreadsheets containing data included in Tables 1 through 10 can be found on the International Accounts data page','http://bea.gov/bea/di1.htm',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-04',81,10,'October',2001,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade, 1997:IV-2001:II',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001isr.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2001-10-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-05',81,10,'October',2001,'Annual NIPA Revision: Newly Available Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001newnipas.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-10-16',NULL,'Interactive Data','http://bea.gov/bea/dn/nipaweb/',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-06',81,10,'October',2001,'Updated Summary NIPA Methodologies',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/NIPAmeth.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-10-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-07',81,10,'October',2001,'Index to the NIPA Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001nipi.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-10-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-08',81,10,'October',2001,'Cross-Border Trade in Services, 1986-2000',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001Crossborder.pdf','International, U.S. international services','2001-10-16',NULL,'Tables','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001is1-2.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-09',81,10,'October',2001,'Errata: Detail for Foreign Direct Investment in the United States',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001Errata.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','2001-10-16',NULL,'Tables','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/1001errA.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-10-10',81,10,'October',2001,'Schedule of BEA News Releases in 2002',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/10october/Release%20dates%202002.pdf',NULL,'2001-10-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-01',81,11,'November',2001,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Eugene P. Seskin, Frederick von Batchelder','U.S. production decreased in the third quarter of 2001 after four quarters of sub-par growth. Exports and nonresidential fixed investment declined sharply for the second consecutive quarter, and consumer spending and State and local government spending increased much less in the third quarter than in the second. Prices paid by U.S. residents decreased in the third quarter. The third-quarter estimates of production and prices reflect the economic effects of the September 11th terrorist attacks (see the box on pages 2 and 3).','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101bsa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-11-19',NULL,'Tables 1 through 5','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/bstabs.xls','Table A','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/bstabs.xls','Adjustment for September 11','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/bstabs.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-02',81,11,'November',2001,'Comparison of BEA Estimates of Personal Income and IRS Estimates of Adjusted Gross Income, 1998-99','Thae S. Park','BEA\'s estimates of personal income and the IRS estimates of adjusted gross income (AGI)--two widely used measures of household income--are reconciled through a series of adjustments for definitional and statistical differences between the two measures. This year\'s reconciliation reflects the recent annual revision of the NIPA\'s and recent updates to the AGI estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101pi_agi.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-11-19',NULL,'Tables 1 through 5','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/agitabs1-5.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-03',81,11,'November',2001,'Gross Domestic Product by Industry for 1998-2000','Sherlene K.S. Lum, Brian C. Moyer','In 2000, real GDP growth for private industries slowed, but that for government picked up. Among the private industries, growth slowed for manufacturing, for construction, for transportation and public utilities, and for mining. Growth for information technology-related industries remained strong. The new estimates for 2000 and the revised estimates for 1998 and 1999 incorporate the results of this year\'s annual revision of the NIPA\'s and newly available source data.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101gdpxind.pdf','National, Gross domestic product by industry','2001-11-19','12/10/2001','Tables 1 through 14','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/indtabs1-14.xls','Tables a through h','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/indtabsa-h.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-04',81,11,'November',2001,'Reconciliation of the U.S.-Canadian Current Account, 1999 and 2000','Anthony DiLullo, Hugh Henderson','Each year, the U.S. and Canadian current-account estimates are reconciled using a common set of definitions, methodologies, and data sources. On the reconciled basis, the U.S. current-account deficits with Canada are larger than those shown in the U.S.-published accounts. For 1999, the deficit on the reconciled basis is $19.1 billion, compared with the U.S.-published deficit of $14.7 billion. For 2000, the reconciled deficit is $39.6 billion, compared with the published deficit of $30.7 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101uscan.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2001-11-19',NULL,'Tables 1 through 7','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/USCtabs1-7.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-05',81,11,'November',2001,'U.S. International Services: Cross-Border Trade in 2000 and Sales Through Affiliates in 1999','Michael A. Mann, Maria Borga','In 2000, U.S. cross-border exports of private services increased 9 percent, to $278.6 billion, and U.S. cross-border imports of these services increased 16 percent, to $200.6 billion. As a result, the U.S. surplus on cross-border trade in services decreased $3.2 billion, to $78.0 billion. In 1999, the most recent year for which the data are available, sales of private services abroad through foreign affiliates of U.S. companies were $338.4 billion, and sales of these services in the United States through U.S. affiliates of foreign companies were $289.3 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11November/1101IntlServ.pdf','International, U.S. international services','2001-11-19','12/7/2001',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-06',81,11,'November',2001,'Personal Income by State, Second Quarter 2001','Duke Tran','Reflecting the slowdown in the growth in personal income for the Nation, the growth in personal income slowed in 40 States in the second quarter of 2001. By State, personal income grew the fastest in Nevada, New Mexico, California, and Florida, and it grew the slowest in North Dakota, Iowa, and West Virginia.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101spi2.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2001-11-19',NULL,'Tables a through d','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/spitabsa-d.xls','Tables 1 and 2','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/spitabs1-2.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-11-07',81,11,'November',2001,'State Per Capita Personal Income, Revised Estimates for 1991-2000',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/1101percap.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2001-11-19',NULL,'Tables 1 and 2','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/11november/pctabs1-2.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-01',81,12,'December',2001,'BEA\'s Preliminary Strategic Plan for 2001-2005','J. Steven Landefeld','BEA has developed a preliminary strategic plan that outlines the major focus of the Bureau\'s work in the next several years. The principal goals consist of making BEA\'s economic accounts and services more responsive to customers; improving the methodologies, source data, and technologies used to prepare the national, industry, international, and regional accounts; attracting, developing, and retaining a top-notch workforce; and upgrading resource management to support these initiatives. The preliminary plan is presented here as part of BEA\'s effort to solicit public review and comment.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201plan.pdf','General','2001-12-14',NULL,'Tables 1 through 12 and Adjustment for September 11','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201bsp.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-02',81,12,'December',2001,'Upcoming Changes in the NAICS-Based 1997 Benchmark Input-Output Accounts','Karen J. Horowitz, Stephanie H. McCulla','This note describes the effects of presenting the 1997 benchmark input-output accounts, which are scheduled to be released at the end of 2002, on a NAICS basis.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201naic.pdf','National, Input-output accounts','2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-03',81,12,'December',2001,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Shelly Smith, Frederick von Batchelder','Real GDP declined 1.1 percent in the third quarter of 2001, according to the \"preliminary\" estimate, after four quarters of anemic growth. The \"advance\" estimate issued a month earlier had shown a 0.4-percent decline. The downward revision was primarily accounted for by a downward revision to the change in private nonfarm inventories and an upward revision to imports of goods. Corporate profits decreased $63.1 billion (8.3 percent at a quarterly rate); about $40 billion of the decrease reflected a reduction in the profits of insurance carriers as a result of the payment of insurance benefits associated with the terrorist attacks of September 11th. The fiscal position of the Federal Government swung sharply from a current surplus of $186.7 billion in the second quarter to a current deficit of $10.2 billion in the third; the downswing reflected the effects of advance refund checks sent to taxpayers in the third quarter. The State and local government current surplus decreased from $21.3 billion to $2.2 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201bsp.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-04',81,12,'December',2001,'Annual Input-Output Accounts of the U.S. Economy, 1998','Mark A. Planting, Peter D. Kuhbach','The 1998 input-output (I-O) accounts, the third annual update of the 1992 benchmark I-O accounts, present a detailed picture of how industries interact to provide input to, and take output from, each other. The 1998 estimates show the continued long-term structural shift in the economy toward the use of services and the rapid growth in the demand for fixed investment commodities, at more than twice the growth rate in the demand for all commodities. In addition, intermediate consumption of business services grew more than 12 percent in 1998, almost five times faster than the growth of intermediate consumption of all other commodities.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201io98.pdf','National, Input-output accounts','2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-05',81,12,'December',2001,'Updated NIPA Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201upda.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-06',81,12,'December',2001,'Federal Personal Income Tax Liabilities and Payments, 1959-99','Thae S. Park',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201tax.pdf','National, Federal personal income tax liabilities and payments','2001-12-14',NULL,'Table 1','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201tax.xls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-07',81,12,'December',2001,'Errata: U.S. International Services',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201err.pdf','International, U.S. international services','2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-08',81,12,'December',2001,'Subject Guide for 2001',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201sg.pdf',NULL,'2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-81-12-09',81,12,'December',2001,'Schedule of BEA News Releases in 2002',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/2001/12december/1201rd.pdf',NULL,'2001-12-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-01',80,1,'January',2000,'GDP: One of the Great Inventions of the 20th Century','J. Steven Landefeld','At a press conference on December 7, 1999, the Department of Commerce announced that it had selected \"the development of the national income and product accounts as its achievement of the century.\" The speakers at the conference and other government policy officials and leading academic economists took the opportunity to affirm the importance of the national accounts to economic analysis and policy making. The accounts were born out of a pressing need for economic information during the Great Depression and World War II, and they have been continually updated and improved so that they provide an accurate, timely, and relevant picture of U.S. economic activity.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/0100od.pdf','General','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-02',80,1,'January',2000,'Zvi Griliches and His Contributions to Economic Measurement','Barbara M. Fraumeni',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0100zvi.pdf','General','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-03',80,1,'January',2000,'Annual Input-Output Accounts of the U.S. Economy, 1996','Sumiye O. Okubo, Ann M. Lawson, Mark A. Planting','The 1996 input-output (I-O) accounts present a detailed picture of how industries interact to provide input to, and take output from, each other. The estimates update the 1992 benchmark I-O accounts and are consistent definitionally and statistically with the recently revised NIPA estimates. The publication of the annual 1996 I-O accounts marks the return of the annual I-O program as part of BEA\'s industry accounts.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/Inputout/2000/0100io.pdf','National, Input-output accounts','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-04',80,1,'January',2000,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 5.7 percent in the third quarter of 1999, according to the NIPA \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 5.5-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.7 percent, the same as the \"preliminary\" estimate. The \"revised\" estimate of corporate profits showed an increase of $3.7 billion (or 0.4 percent at a quarterly rate) in the third quarter; the \"preliminary\" estimate had shown an increase of $8.2 billion (or 0.9 percent).','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0100bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-05',80,1,'January',2000,'U.S. International Transactions, Third Quarter 1999','Harlan W. King','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $9.0 billion, to $89.9 billion, in the third quarter of 1999. Most of the increase was accounted for by an increase in the deficit on goods, as imports increased twice as much as exports increased. In the financial account, net recorded inflows decreased $13.9 billion, to $105.7 billion. Inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States and outflows for U.S.-owned assets abroad both slowed sharply, but the slowdown in inflows, which reflected a sharp dropoff in foreign acquisitions of U.S. companies, exceeded that in outflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/0100it.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-06',80,1,'January',2000,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade, 1977:I--1999:III',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0100is.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-07',80,1,'January',2000,'Errata: National Income and Product Accounts',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0100err.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-01-08',80,1,'January',2000,'An Ownership-Based Disaggregation of the U.S. Current Account, 1982--97','Jeffrey H. Lowe',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/0100iid.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-01-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-01',80,2,'February',2000,'Comparison of BEA Estimates of Personal Income and IRS Estimates of Adjusted Gross Income','Thae S. Park','The BEA estimates of personal income and the IRS estimates of adjusted gross income (AGI)---two widely used measures of household income---are reconciled through a series of adjustments for definitional differences between the two measures. This reconciliation incorporates the results of the recent comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s, updates to the AGI estimates, and several improvements to the reconciliation items.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0200agi.pdf','National, BEA personal income and IRS adjusted gross income','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-02',80,2,'February',2000,'Accounting for Subsoil Mineral Resources','The National Research Council - the Panel on Integrated Environmental and Economic Accounting, William D. Nordhaus, Edward C. Kokkenlenberg','[Reprint of chapter 3 of Nature\'s Numbers: Expanding the National Economic Accounts to Include the Environment] Last summer, a blue-ribbon panel of the National Academy of Sciences\' National Research Council completed a congressionally mandated review of BEA\'s prototype integrated economic and environmental accounts. As part of its promise to inform users of the results of this evaluation, BEA is reprinting chapters from the panel\'s final report.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0200srm.pdf','International, Satellite accounts','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-03',80,2,'February',2000,'Industrial Composition of State Earnings in 1958--98','G. Andrew Bernat, Jr., Eric S. Repice','The industrial composition of earnings across States has become more similar over time. This convergence primarily reflects the relatively stronger growth in services than in farming and manufacturing; services-producing industries tend to be more evenly distributed across the Nation than goods-producing industries. In 1998, the States with industrial compositions that were most similar to that of the United States were California, Washington, Arizona, Pennsylvania, and Missouri. The States that were least similar were Wyoming, Alaska, Nevada, Hawaii, and New Mexico.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/0200rea.pdf','Regional, Industrial composition of State earnings','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-04',80,2,'February',2000,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff','U.S. economic activity registered another strong increase in the fourth quarter of 1999, while inflation picked up somewhat. Real GDP increased 5.8 percent after increasing 5.7 percent in the third quarter. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.3 percent after increasing 1.7 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0200bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-05',80,2,'February',2000,'Motor Vehicles, 1999','Ralph W. Morris','Sales of motor vehicles surged to a record 17.4 million units in 1999 from 16.0 million units in 1998. Sales of new trucks again increased strongly, reaching a record 8.7 million units; sales of new cars also increased to 8.7 million units, following 4 consecutive years of declines.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0200mv.pdf','National, Motor vehicles','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-06',80,2,'February',2000,'State Personal Income, Third Quarter 1999','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation increased 1.3 percent in the third quarter of 1999, the same pace as in the second quarter. In the third quarter, the States with the fastest growth in personal income were Nevada, Arizona, and Florida. The States with the slowest growth were North Dakota, South Dakota, and North Carolina.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/0200spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-02-07',80,2,'February',2000,'Comprehensive NIPA Revision: Newly Available Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0200nipa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-02-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-01',80,3,'March',2000,'Accounting for Renewable and Environmental Resources','The National Research Council - the Panel on Integrated Environmental and Economic Accounting, William D. Nordhaus, Edward C. Kokkenlenberg','[Reprint of chapter 4 of Nature\'s Numbers: Expanding the National Economic Accounts to Include the Environment] Last summer, a blue-ribbon panel of the National Academy of Sciences\' National Research Council completed a congressionally mandated review of BEA\'s prototype integrated economic and environmental accounts. As part of its promise to inform users of the results of this evaluation, BEA is reprinting chapters from the panel\'s final report.\\n','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0300are.pdf','International, Satellite accounts','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-02',80,3,'March',2000,'An Examination of the Low Rates of Return of Foreign-Owned U.S. Companies','Raymond J. Mataloni, Jr.','In 1988-97, the average rate of return on assets (ROA) of foreign-owned nonfinancial companies, at 5.1 percent, was 2.2 percentage points below that of U.S.-owned companies; over the period, the ROA gap narrowed to about 1 percentage point in 1997. Among several factors that may help explain the lower ROA of foreign-owned companies, age and market share were found to be significant, and industry mix and shifting of profits outside the United States using transfer prices were found to be relatively insignificant. These findings are based on newly developed estimates of the rate of return for foreign-owned U.S. nonfinancial companies that are disaggregated by industry and valued in current-period prices.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/2000/0300rr.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-03',80,3,'March',2000,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff','Real GDP increased 6.9 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999, according to the \"preliminary\" estimate; the \"advance\" estimate issued last month had shown a 5.8-percent increase. The upward revision reflected upward revisions to consumer spending, to State and local government spending, to exports of goods, and to private nonfarm inventory investment. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.3 percent in the fourth quarter, the same as the previously published increase.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0300bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-04',80,3,'March',2000,'Federal Personal Income Tax Liabilities and Payments, 1959-97','Thae S. Park','BEA\'s estimates of Federal personal income tax liabilities and payments have been revised, beginning with 1959, to incorporate the results of the recent comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s and newly available tax return data from the Internal Revenue Service. Since 1992, the differences between liabilities and payments have generally been small; in 1997, payments exceeded liabilities by $2.3 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0300fpi.pdf','National, Federal personal income tax liabilities and payments','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-05',80,3,'March',2000,'Federal Budget Estimates, Fiscal Year 2001','Laura M. Beall, Sean P. Keehan','Each year, BEA prepares a \"translation\" of the administration\'s budget that puts the budget\'s receipts and outlays on a basis that is consistent with the framework of the NIPA\'s. For fiscal year 2001, the Federal current surplus on the NIPA basis would be $171.1 billion, compared with the surplus of $184.0 billion in the administration\'s budget. The budget estimate of receipts would exceed the NIPA estimate of current receipts by $2.4 billion, and the NIPA estimate of current expenditures would exceed the budget estimate of outlays by $10.5 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0300fbe.pdf','National, Federal budget estimates','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-03-06',80,3,'March',2000,'Errata: Industrial Composition of State Earnings in 1958-98',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/0300errata.pdf','Regional, Industrial composition of State earnings','2000-03-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-01',80,4,'April',2000,'Improved Estimates of the National Income and Product Accounts for 1929-99: Results of the Comprehensive Revision','Brent R. Moulton','On March 30, 2000, as part of the comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s, BEA released revised NIPA estimates for 1929-58 that incorporated the definitional and statistical changes that had been incorporated earlier into the estimates beginning with 1959. In addition, BEA released revised estimates beginning with 1959 that incorporated corrections and a previously announced methodological improvement. The revisions were not sizable enough to affect the average annual growth rate in real GDP for 1929-58 or for 1959-98, but the growth rates for individual years were revised by as much as 0.5 percentage point.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0400nipa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-02',80,4,'April',2000,'Fixed Assets and Consumer Durable Goods: Estimates for 1925-98 and New NIPA Table--Changes in Net Stock of Produced Assets','Shelby W. Herman','As part of the comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s, BEA has released new estimates of fixed assets and consumer durable goods (formerly \"fixed reproducible tangible wealth\") for 1998 and revised estimates for 1925-97. These estimates incorporate a number of definitional and statistical improvements, including the recognition of business and government expenditures for software as fixed investment and a new pattern of depreciation for personal computers. For 1925-98, the net stock at current cost grew at an average annual rate of 6.3 percent, and the net stock at real cost grew at a rate of 2.9 percent. In addition, as part of a long-term effort to integrate the estimates of stocks and flows, BEA has introduced a new NIPA table that shows the changes in the net stock of produced assets.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0400fxacdg.pdf','National, Fixed assets and consumer durable goods','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-03',80,4,'April',2000,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins, Mary L. Roy','Real GDP increased 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999, according to the \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate released last month had shown a 6.9-percent increase. Corporate profits increased $35.3 billion (4.0 percent at a quarterly rate) in the fourth quarter. The Federal Government current surplus decreased $21.6 billion, to $112.2 billion, and the State and local government current surplus increased $19.9 billion, to $68.8 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0400bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-04',80,4,'April',2000,'U.S. International Transactions, Fourth Quarter and Year 1999','Christopher L. Bach','In the fourth quarter of 1999, the U.S. current-account deficit increased $10.7 billion, to $99.8 billion; the deficit on goods and services, the deficit on income, and net unilateral current transfers all contributed to the increase. In the financial account, net recorded inflows decreased $3.4 billion, to $90.9 billion; financial inflows decreased more than financial outflows. In the year 1999, the U.S. current-account deficit increased $118.3 billion, to $338.9 billion; the increase was mostly accounted for by a sharp rise in the deficit on goods and services. In the financial account, net recorded inflows increased $168.4 billion, to $378.2 billion; financial inflows accelerated much more than financial outflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/0400it.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-05',80,4,'April',2000,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0400niw.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-06',80,4,'April',2000,'National Income and Product Accounts',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0400nipatables32.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-07',80,4,'April',2000,'National Income and Product Accounts Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0400nipatables36.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-04-08',80,4,'April',2000,'GDP and Other Major NIPA Series, 1929-99',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0400nips.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-04-26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-05-01',80,5,'May',2000,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff','U.S. economic activity continued to increase strongly in the first quarter of 2000, while inflation picked up. Real GDP increased 5.4 percent after increasing 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 3.2 percent after increasing 2.3 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/national/nipa/2000/0500bsa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-05-18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-05-02',80,5,'May',2000,'State and Local Government Fiscal Position in 1999','Janet H. Kmitch, Bruce E. Baker','In 1999, the current surplus of State and local governments--a measure of their net saving--increased $9.3 billion, to $51.0 billion, as current receipts increased more than current expenditures. \"Net lending or net borrowing,\" an alternative measure of the fiscal position, was introduced in the recent comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s. This measure showed that the longer term financing requirements of governments continued to decrease; it was -$13.8 billion in 1999, compared with -$16.8 billion in 1998.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/national/niparel/2000/0500slp.pdf','National, State and local government fiscal position','2000-05-18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-05-03',80,5,'May',2000,'U.S. Transportation Satellite Accounts for 1996','Bingsong Fang, Xiaoli Han, Sumiye Okubo, Ann M. Lawson','The U.S. transportation satellite accounts (TSA\'s) have been updated to present estimates for 1996. Like the 1992 TSA\'s, the 1996 TSA\'s extend the input-output accounts to provide a more comprehensive picture of the role of transportation in the U.S. economy. The TSA\'s show that the economy produced and used $673 billion of transportation gross output in 1996, up 23 percent from 1992. The contribution of transportation activities to GDP deceased slightly from 5.0 percent in 1992 to 4.8 percent in 1996.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/national/Inputout/2000/0500tsa.pdf','International, Satellite accounts','2000-05-18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-05-04',80,5,'May',2000,'Errata : Fixed Assets and Consumer Durable Goods',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/National/NIPAREL/2000/0500err.pdf','National, Fixed assets and consumer durable goods','2000-05-18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-05-05',80,5,'May',2000,'NIPA Component Contributions Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/national/NIPA/2000/0500cct.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-05-18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-01',80,6,'June',2000,'Note on Rates of Return for Domestic Nonfinancial Corporations: Revised Estimates for 1960-98','Daniel Larkins',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/National/NIPA/2000/0600nrr.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-02',80,6,'June',2000,'Government Spending by Function: A New Presentation','Karl Galbraith',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/National/NIPAREL/2000/0600gf.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-03',80,6,'June',2000,'Improved Estimates of Gross Product by Industry for 1947-98','Sherlene K.S. Lum, Brian C. Moyer, Robert E. Yuskavage','The estimates of gross product by industry have been revised to incorporate the results of the recent comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s, newly available source data, and several methodological changes. The most significant element of the revision is the development of an integrated set of estimates of gross output, intermediate inputs, and gross product originating (GPO) for all industries. This result enabled the extension of the double-deflation method for computing real GPO to all industries, thereby improving the reliability of the estimates and their consistency with the NIPA estimates. The revisions did not greatly affect the growth rates for real GPO: Real GPO growth for private industries was revised up 0.3 percentage point, the same as the upward revision to real GDP.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/National/NIPAREL/2000/0600gpi.pdf','National, Gross domestic product by industry','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-04',80,6,'June',2000,'Comprehensive Revision of State Personal Income: Revised Estimates for 1969-98 and Preliminary Estimates for 1999','Robert L. Brown, Kathy A. Albetski, Jeffrey L. Newman, Adrienne T. Pilot, Duke Tran','On May 17, 2000, BEA released revised estimates of State personal income for 1969-99 that incorporated the results of the most recent comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s, newly available benchmark source data, and improved methods for preparing the State estimates. In general, the State estimates were revised up, reflecting several major improvements that were introduced into the national estimates. This release represents a speedup of nearly 6 months in the availability of State personal income estimates that are consistent with the recently revised NIPA estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/regional/perinc/2000/0600spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-05',80,6,'June',2000,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff, Mary L. Roy','Real GDP increased 5.4 percent in the first quarter of 2000 after in-creasing 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999; the price index for gross domestic purchases increased 3.2 percent after increasing 2.3 percent. Corporate profits increased $34.5 billion (3.8 percent at a quarterly rate) in the first quarter. The Federal Government current surplus increased $74.1 billion, to $186.3 billion, and the State and local government current surplus decreased $12.1 billion, to $56.7 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/National/NIPA/2000/0600bsP.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-06',80,6,'June',2000,'Foreign Direct Investment in the United States: New Investment in 1999','Ned G. Howenstine, Rosaria Troia','Outlays by foreign investors to acquire or establish businesses in the United States increased to a record $282.9 billion in 1999 from $215.3 billion in 1998. The exceptionally high outlays in both years reflect a worldwide boom in merger and acquisition activity, the continuing strength of the U.S. economy, and the increasing number and size of large investments.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/internat/FDINVEST/2000/0600fdi.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-06-07',80,6,'June',2000,'Subject Guide for Volume 80, Numbers 1-6',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/beawide/2000/0600sg.pdf',NULL,'2000-06-23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-01',80,7,'July',2000,'U.S. Travel and Tourism Satellite Accounts for 1996 and 1997','David I. Kass, Sumiye Okubo','The U.S. travel and tourism satellite accounts (TTSA\'s) have been updated to present estimates for 1996 and 1997. Like the 1992 TTSA\'s, the 1996 and 1997 TTSA\'s extend the input-output accounts to present a more comprehensive picture of the impact of travel and tourism activities on the U.S. economy. According to the TTSA\'s, final domestic demand for travel and tourism grew at an average annual rate of 6.9 percent from 1992 to 1997, while GDP increased at an average annual rate of 5.6 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/Inputout/2000/0700tta.pdf','International, Satellite accounts','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-02',80,7,'July',2000,'U.S. International Transactions, Revised Estimates for 1982-99','Christopher L. Bach','This year\'s annual revision of the international transactions accounts incorporates improvements to the investment income and portfolio capital accounts. The estimates of investment income are revised to incorporate the final results of the U.S. Treasury Department\'s Benchmark Survey of U.S. Portfolio Investment Abroad as of December 31, 1997. Net U.S. purchases of foreign securities are revised to reflect improvements in the accounting for large-scale foreign acquisitions of U.S. companies and to reflect other improvements in the coverage of U.S. transactions in foreign securities. The revised estimate of the U.S. current-account deficit for 1999 is -$331.5 billion, compared with the previously published estimate of -$338.9 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/0700itr.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-03',80,7,'July',2000,'Comprehensive Revision of Local Area Personal Income: Revised Estimates for 1969-97 and New Estimates for 1998','Jeffrey L. Newman, Kathy A. Albetski, Robert L. Brown, Adrienne T. Pilot','On June 15, 2000, BEA released estimates of local area personal income for 1969-98 that incorporated the results of the most recent comprehensive revisions of State personal income and of the NIPA\'s as well as improved methods for preparing the estimates and newly available data from regular sources. In general, the local area estimates were revised up, primarily reflecting the NIPA definitional change that reclassified government employee retirement plans. This release represents a speedup of about a year in the availability of local area estimates of personal income that are consistent with the recently revised State personal income estimates and NIPA estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/0700lap.pdf','Regional, Local area personal income','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-04',80,7,'July',2000,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 5.5 percent in the first quarter of 2000 after increasing 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1999; the price index for gross domestic purchases increased 3.5 percent after increasing 2.3 percent. Corporate profits increased $46.2 billion (5.0 percent at a quarterly rate) in the first quarter.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0700bsf.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-05',80,7,'July',2000,'U.S. Multinational Companies: Operations in 1998','Raymond J. Mataloni, Jr.','Growth slowed in three key measures--gross product, employment, and capital expenditures--of the operations of U.S. multinational companies in 1998 after strong growth in 1997. The gross product of U.S. parent companies increased 2.2 percent in 1998 after increasing 6.3 percent in 1997, and the gross product of the majority-owned affiliates of U.S. companies declined 1.9 percent after increasing 4.5 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/internat/USINVEST/2000/0700mnc.pdf','International, U.S. multinational companies','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-06',80,7,'July',2000,'The International Investment Position of the United States at Yearend 1999','Russell B. Scholl','The net international investment position of the United States changed little in 1999: At yearend, it was -$1,082 billion on a current-cost basis and -$1,474 billion on a market-value basis. Large net financial inflows were offset by greater price appreciation in U.S.-owned assets abroad than in foreign-owned assets in the United States.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/internat/BPA/2000/0700iip.pdf','International, U.S. international investment position','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-07',80,7,'July',2000,'Direct Investment Positions for 1999: Country and Industry Detail','Sylvia E. Bargas','The U.S. direct investment position abroad valued at historical cost increased 12 percent in 1999, and the foreign direct investment position in the United States valued at historical cost increased 24 percent. The strong growth in both positions reflected the global boom in merger and acquisition activity, favorable economic conditions in the United States, Europe, and Canada, and improved economic conditions in the Asia and Pacific area.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/internat/fdinvest/2000/0700dip.pdf','International, Direct investment positions: Country and industry detail','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-07-08',80,7,'July',2000,'U.S. International Transactions, First Quarter 2000','Douglas B. Weinberg','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $6.1 billion, to $102.3 billion, in the first quarter of 2000; the increase was more than accounted for by a large increase in the deficit on goods. In the financial account, net recorded inflows increased $2.0 billion, to $71.7 billion; financial inflows increased more than financial outflows.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/0700ita.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-07-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-01',80,8,'August',2000,'Annual Revision of the National Income and Product Accounts: Annual Estimates, 1997-99, and Quarterly Estimates, 1997:I-2000:I','Eugene P. Seskin, David F. Sullivan','The revised NIPA estimates do not significantly alter the picture of the U.S. economy that was shown in the previously published estimates. Over the period covered by the revisions, the average annual growth rate of real GDP was revised up slightly, from 4.5 percent to 4.6 percent, and the average annual rate of increase in the price index for gross domestic purchases was unrevised at 1.5 percent. The revised estimates reflect the incorporation of regular source data and the introduction of changes in the methodology for preparing the estimates; for example, the estimates of employer contributions to group health insurance are now based on data collected in the new medical expenditure panel survey.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0800nipr.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-02',80,8,'August',2000,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris','Real GDP continued to increase strongly in the second quarter of 2000, up 5.2 percent after a 4.8-percent increase in the first quarter. In contrast, real final sales of domestic product slowed to a 4.2-percent increase from a 6.7-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases slowed to a 2.2-percent increase from a 3.8-percent increase.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0800bsa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-03',80,8,'August',2000,'U.S. Affiliates of Foreign Companies: Operations in 1998','William J. Zeile','The current-dollar gross product of U.S. affiliates of foreign companies increased 7 percent in 1998, primarily reflecting record levels of new foreign investment. The U.S.-affiliate share of gross product originating in U.S. private industries edged up from 6.2 percent in 1997 to 6.3 percent in 1998. By country of ownership, the United Kingdom remained the largest investing country in 1998, and Germany overtook Japan as the second largest as a result of new acquisitions of U.S. companies.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/2000/0800fdi.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-04',80,8,'August',2000,'State Personal Income, First Quarter 2000','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation slowed to a 1.6-percent increase in the first quarter of 2000 from a 1.9-percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1999. In the first quarter, personal income grew the fastest in Vermont, North Carolina, Alaska, Georgia, and Florida. Personal income declined in North Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, South Dakota, and Iowa.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/0800spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-05',80,8,'August',2000,'National Income and Product Accounts Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0800nipt.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-06',80,8,'August',2000,'GDP and Other Major NIPA Series, 1929-2000:I',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0800gdp.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-08-07',80,8,'August',2000,'Errata: U.S. Travel and Tourism Satellite Accounts for 1996 and 1997',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/INPUTOUT/2000/0800tsaerr.pdf','International, Satellite accounts','2000-08-16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-01',80,9,'September',2000,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Jennifer S. Argueta, Steven J. Andrews','Real GDP accelerated modestly to a 5.3-percent increase in the second quarter of 2000 from a 4.8-percent increase in the first quarter; in contrast, real final sales of domestic product decelerated sharply to a 3.5-percent increase from a 6.7-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.3 percent after increasing 3.8 percent. Corporate profits increased $27.7 billion (3.0 percent at a quarterly rate) in the second quarter after increasing $43.1 billion (4.8 percent) in the first. The Federal Government surplus increased $2.0 billion, to $237.8 billion, in the second quarter after increasing $92.5 billion in the first. The State and local government surplus increased $2.2 billion, to $54.2 billion, after decreasing $14.6 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0900bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-02',80,9,'September',2000,'Customer Service Report for Fiscal Year 2000','Verna M. Learnard',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/0900csr.pdf','General','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-03',80,9,'September',2000,'Annual NIPA Revision: Newly Available Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/0900nat.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-04',80,9,'September',2000,'Fixed Assets and Consumer Durable Goods for 1925-99','Shelby W. Herman',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/0900cdg.pdf','National, Fixed assets and consumer durable goods','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-05',80,9,'September',2000,'Foreign Direct Investment in the United States: Detail for Historical-Cost Position and Related Capital and Income Flows, 1999','Jeffrey H. Lowe',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/2000/0900fdi.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-09-06',80,9,'September',2000,'U.S. Direct Investment Abroad: Detail for Historical-Cost Position and Related Capital and Income Flows, 1999','Jeffrey H. Lowe',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/USINVEST/2000/0900usd.pdf','International, U.S. direct investment abroad','2000-09-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-01',80,10,'October',2000,'Gross State Product by Industry, 1977-98','Richard M. Beemiller, Clifford H. Woodruff III','BEA\'s estimates of gross state product (GSP) by industry have been revised to incorporate the most recent comprehensive revisions of the NIPA\'s, of the national estimates of gross product by industry, and of the estimates of State personal income. In 1997-98, the State with the fastest growth in real GSP was Arizona (7.5 percent annual rate), followed by Oregon (7.2 percent) and Nevada (6.9 percent); the States with negative growth were Hawaii (-0.5 percent) and Alaska (-0.4 percent). The State with the largest share of nominal GSP in 1998 was California (12.8 percent), followed by New York (8.1 percent) and Texas (7.4 percent).','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/GSP/2000/1000gsp.pdf','Regional, Gross state product','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-02',80,10,'October',2000,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 5.6 percent in the second quarter of 2000, according to the \"final\" NIPA estimates; the upward revision of 0.3 percentage point from the \"preliminary\" estimate primarily reflected a downward revision to imports of services and an upward revision to exports of services. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.1 percent; the downward revision of 0.2 percentage point primarily reflected downward revisions to the prices of personal consumption expenditures for services. Corporate profits increased $27.3 billion (2.9 percent at a quarterly rate) in the second quarter.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1000bsf.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-03',80,10,'October',2000,'U.S. International Transactions, Second Quarter 2000','Harlan W. King','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $4.6 billion, to $106.1 billion, in the second quarter of 2000; nearly all of the increase was accounted for by an increase in the deficit on goods. In the financial account, net recorded inflows increased $91.5 billion, to $149.1 billion; financial outflows slowed substantially, while financial inflows remained strong.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/1000ita.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-04',80,10,'October',2000,'U.S. International Services: Cross-Border Trade in 1999 and Sales Through Affiliates in 1998','Michael A. Mann, Laura L. Brokenbaugh, Sylvia E. Bargas','In 1999, U.S. cross-border exports of private services increased 4 percent to $254.7 billion, and U.S. cross-border imports of these services increased 4 percent to $174.8 billion; as a result, the U.S. surplus on cross-border trade in services increased $3.3 billion, to $79.8 billion. In 1998, sales of private services abroad by foreign affiliates of U.S. companies increased 21 percent to $309.0 billion, and sales of services in the United States by U.S. affiliates of foreign companies increased 14 percent to $255.1 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/INTSERV/2000/1000is.pdf','International, U.S. international services','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-05',80,10,'October',2000,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade, 1996:IV-2000:II',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/1000isr.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory-sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-06',80,10,'October',2000,'Annual NIPA Revision: Newly Available Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1000nat.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-07',80,10,'October',2000,'Updated Summary NIPA Methodologies',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1000Nsum.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-08',80,10,'October',2000,'Index to the NIPA Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1000nipi.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-09',80,10,'October',2000,'State Personal Income, Revised Estimates for 1997-99','Jeffrey L. Newman',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/1000spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-10-10',80,10,'October',2000,'Schedule of BEA News Releases in 2001',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/1000rd.pdf',NULL,'2000-10-19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-11-01',80,11,'November',2000,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris','The growth in the U.S. economy slowed in the third quarter of 2000, while inflation remained moderate. Real GDP increased 2.7 percent, less than half as much as the average increase in the preceding four quarters; the price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.4 percent, about the same as the average increase in the preceding four quarters.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1100bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-11-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-11-02',80,11,'November',2000,'Comparison of BEA Estimates of Personal Income and IRS Estimates of Adjusted Gross Income: New Estimates for 1998 and Revised Estimates for 1997','Thae S. Park','BEA\'s estimates of personal income and the IRS estimates of adjusted gross income (AGI)--two widely used measures of household income--are reconciled through a series of adjustments for definitional differences between the two measures. This year\'s reconciliation reflects the recent annual revision of the national income and product accounts and recent updates to the AGI estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/1100pinagi.pdf','National, BEA personal income and IRS adjusted gross income','2000-11-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-11-03',80,11,'November',2000,'Reconciliation of the U.S.-Canadian Current Account, 1998 and 1999','Anthony DiLullo, Hugh Henderson','Each year, the U.S. and Canadian current-account estimates are reconciled to show how they would appear if both countries used the same definitions, methodologies, and data sources. After the reconciliation, the U.S. current-account deficits with Canada are larger than those that are shown in the U.S.-published accounts: For 1998, the deficit on the reconciled basis is $9.6 billion, compared with the U.S.-published deficit of $4.4 billion; for 1999, the reconciled deficit is $19.5 billion, compared with the published deficit of $15.1 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/2000/1100us-can.pdf','International, Reconciliation of the U.S.-Canadian current account','2000-11-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-11-04',89,11,'November',2000,'State Personal Income, Second Quarter 2000','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation increased 1.7 percent in the second quarter of 2000 after increasing 1.6 percent in the first quarter. In the second quarter, personal income grew the fastest in Nevada, Delaware, and Iowa. Personal income grew the slowest in Connecticut, Arizona, North Dakota, and New Hampshire.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/2000/1100spiq.pdf','Regional, State personal income','2000-11-21',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-01',80,12,'December',2000,'A Note on the Impact of Hedonics and Computers on Real GDP','J. Steven Landefeld, Bruce T. Grimm','A review of the data on hedonic price indexes and their impact on real GDP growth shows no evidence of an overstatement in the measured decline in computer prices. The hedonic price indexes for computers produce results that are quite robust and that are virtually the same as those produced by a carefully constructed traditional price index for computers.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/1200hm.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-02',80,12,'December',2000,'Business Situation','R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Jennifer S. Argueta, Steven J. Andrews','The growth in the U.S. economy slowed in the third quarter of 2000, while inflation remained moderate. Real GDP increased 2.4 percent, less than half as much as the average increase in the preceding four quarters; the prices of gross domestic purchases increased 2.3 percent, about the same as the average increase in the preceding four quarters. Corporate profits increased $7.6 billion (0.8 percent at a quarterly rate) in the third quarter after increasing $27.3 billion (2.9 percent) in the second. The Federal Government current surplus increased $13.4 billion, to $254.3 billion, in the third quarter after increasing $5.1 billion in the second. The State and local government current surplus increased $4.1 billion, to $64.2 billion, after increasing $8.1 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1200bsp.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-03',80,12,'December',2000,'Gross Domestic Product by Industry for 1997-99','Sherlene K.S. Lum, Brian C. Moyer','New estimates of gross domestic product by industry for 1999 and revised estimates for 1997 and 1998 incorporate the results of this year\'s annual revision of the NIPA\'s and newly available source data. According to these estimates, the long-term structural shift in the U.S. economy from goods-producing industries to services-producing industries continued. The revisions to the real growth rate of private industries were small, but the revisions to the growth rates for some of the individual industry groups were substantial.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/1200gpi.pdf','National, Gross domestic product by industry','2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-04',80,12,'December',2000,'Revised Estimates of Real Gross Product of Nonfinancial Corporate Business for 1997-2000',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/2000/1200gncb.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-05',80,12,'December',2000,'Federal Personal Income Tax Liabilities and Payments, 1959-98','Thae S. Park',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/2000/1200fpit.pdf','National, Federal personal income tax liabilities and payments','2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-06',80,12,'December',2000,'Subject Guide',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/1200sg.pdf',NULL,'2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-80-12-07',80,12,'December',2000,'Schedule of BEA News Releases in 2001',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/2000/1200rd.pdf',NULL,'2000-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-01',79,1,'January',1999,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 3.7 percent in the third quarter of 1998, according to the \"final\" NIPA estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 3.9-percent increase. A downward revision to net exports more than offset an upward revision to business fixed investment. Corporate profits increased $6.4 billion (0.8 percent at a quarterly rate) in the third quarter, as an increase in profits of domestic nonfinancial corporations more than offset a decrease in profits from the rest of the world.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0199bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-02',79,1,'January',1999,'U.S. International Transactions, Third Quarter 1998','Harlan W. King','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $4.6 billion, to $61.3 billion, in the third quarter of 1998. The increase was accounted for by an increase in the deficit on investment income, a decrease in the surplus on services, and an increase in net unilateral transfers. In the capital account, capital outflows decreased more than capital inflows. U.S. assets abroad increased $48.1 billion after increasing $109.8 billion, and foreign assets in the United States increased $112.9 billion after increasing $164.9 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0199bop.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-03',79,1,'January',1999,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/0199niw.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-04',79,1,'January',1999,'Robert Eisner\'s Contributions to Economic Measurement',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0199od.pdf','General','1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-05',79,1,'January',1999,'Announcement of Availability of Local Area Estimates',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0199rem.pdf','Regional, Local area personal income','1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-01-06',79,1,'January',1999,'1999 Release Dates for BEA Estimates',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/0199rd.pdf',NULL,'1999-01-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-02-01',79,2,'February',1999,'Note on the Personal Saving Rate','Daniel Larkins',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0299cba.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-02-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-02-02',79,2,'February',1999,'Upcoming Changes in the Classification of Current and Capital Transactions in the U.S. International Accounts',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0299bop2.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-02-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-02-03',79,2,'February',1999,'U.S. Resource Flows to Developing Countries and Multilateral Organizations, 1993-97','William McCormick',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0299bop.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-02-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-02-04',79,2,'February',1999,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff','U.S. economic activity picked up in the fourth quarter of 1998: Real GDP increased 5.6 percent after increasing 3.7 percent in the third quarter. Inflation remained low: The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 0.9 percent after increasing 0.7 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0299bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-02-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-02-05',79,2,'February',1999,'Personal Income by State and Region, Third Quarter 1998','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation increased $78.9 billion, or 1.1 percent, in the third quarter of 1998. By region, the largest increases were in the Southeast and the Far West. By State, personal income grew rapidly in Nevada, Colorado, Washington, and Arizona. Personal income declined in Montana and grew slowly in Indiana, South Dakota, and Iowa.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0299read.pdf','Regional, State personal income','1999-02-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-03-01',79,3,'March',1999,'Wassily Leontief and His Contributions to Economic Accounting','J. Steven Landefeld, Stephanie H. McCulla',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/Inputout/1999/0399leon.pdf','General','1999-03-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-03-02',79,3,'March',1999,'A Tour of BEA\'s Web Site',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/0399cba.pdf','General','1999-03-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-03-03',79,3,'March',1999,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris','The \"preliminary\" estimate of real GDP shows a 6.1-percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1998 after an increase of 3.7 percent in the third quarter. The 6.1-percent increase is 0.5 percentage point higher than the \"advance\" estimate published last month; the upward revision reflects a downward revision to imports of goods, which are subtracted in the calculation of GDP, and upward revisions to personal consumption expenditures for nondurable goods and to exports of goods. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 0.8 percent in the fourth quarter after increasing 0.7 percent in the third.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0399bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-03-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-03-04',79,3,'March',1999,'Federal Budget Estimates, Fiscal Year 2000','Kurt S. Bersani, Laura M. Bilenki','Each year, BEA prepares a \"translation\" of the administration\'s budget that puts the budget\'s receipts and outlays on a basis that is consistent with the framework of the NIPA\'s. For fiscal year 2000, the Federal current surplus on the NIPA basis would be $119.1 billion, compared with the administration\'s budget surplus of $117.3 billion. The NIPA estimate of receipts would exceed the budget estimate of receipts by $104.0 billion, and the NIPA estimate of current expenditures would exceed the budget estimate of outlays by $102.2 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/0399gd.pdf','National, Federal budget estimates','1999-03-10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-04-01',79,4,'April',1999,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins, Florence H. Campi','Real GDP increased 6.0 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998, according to the NIPA \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 6.1-percent increase. Corporate profits decreased $5.3 billion (0.6 percent at a quarterly rate) in the fourth quarter. The Federal Government current surplus decreased $26.2 billion, to $65.8 billion, in the fourth quarter, and the State and local government current surplus increased $21.8 billion, to $170.5 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0499bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-04-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-04-02',79,4,'April',1999,'State and Local Government Fiscal Position in 1998','Janet H. Kmitch, Bruce E. Baker','The current surplus of State and local governments increased $16.1 billion, to $150.2 billion, in 1998. As in recent years, the increase in receipts exceeded the increase in current expenditures. For 1999, available information suggests that receipts will decelerate and that current expenditures will accelerate, so that the current surplus is expected to change little.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/0499gov.pdf','National, State and local government fiscal position','1999-04-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-04-03',79,4,'April',1999,'U.S. International Transactions, Fourth Quarter and Year 1998','Christopher L. Bach','In the fourth quarter of 1998, the U.S. current-account deficit decreased to $63.8 billion from $65.7 billion in the third quarter; the decrease was attributable to decreases in the deficits on goods and on investment income and an increase in the surplus on services. In the capital account, foreign assets in the United States increased $183.1 billion after increasing $98.7 billion, and U.S. assets abroad increased $88.8 billion after increasing $60.4 billion. For the year 1998, the U.S. current-account deficit increased to $233.4 billion from $155.2 billion in 1997; the increase was largely attributable to an increase in the deficit on goods, but an increase in the deficit on investment income and a decrease in the surplus on services also contributed. In the capital account, foreign assets in the United States increased $542.5 billion after increasing $733.4 billion, and U.S. assets abroad increased $305.4 billion after increasing $478.5 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0499bop.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-04-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-04-04',79,4,'April',1999,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/0499niw.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','1999-04-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-05-01',79,5,'May',1999,'Regional Patterns in the Location of Foreign-Owned U.S. Manufacturing Establishments','Dale P. Shannon, William J. Zeile, Kenneth P. Johnson','An analysis of the employment of foreign-owned U.S. manufacturing establishments by BEA economic area indicates that the regional distribution of newly built, or \"greenfield,\" establishments is relatively concentrated in parts of New England and the Southeast. By country of ownership, the regional patterns for Canadian- and Japanese-owned greenfield establishments differ noticeably from those of other foreign-owned greenfield establishments. These findings are based on a new data set on foreign-owned U.S. manufacturing establishments that BEA prepared from microdata files that were made available by arrangement with the Census Bureau\'s Center for Economic Studies.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0599iid.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','1999-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-05-02',79,5,'May',1999,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris','U.S. economic activity slowed but remained strong in the first quarter of 1999: Real GDP increased 4.5 percent after increasing 6.0 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998. Inflation remained low: The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.0 percent after increasing 0.9 percent.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0599bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-05-03',79,5,'May',1999,'Personal Income and Per Capita Personal Income by State and Region, 1998','Duke Tran','Per capita personal income for the Nation was $26,412 in 1998, up 4.4 percent from $25,288 in 1997. By State, Connecticut had the highest per capita income, at $37,598, and Mississippi had the lowest, at $18,958. The States with the fastest growth in per capita income were North Dakota, Colorado, Washington, Texas, Vermont, and Massachusetts; the States with the slowest growth were Hawaii, Wyoming, Nevada, Montana, and Alaska.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0599read.pdf','Regional, Per capita personal income, State personal income','1999-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-05-04',79,5,'May',1999,'Local Area Personal Income, 1982–97','Wallace K. Bailey','BEA has released new estimates of personal income for 1997 and revised estimates for 1982--96 for counties, metropolitan areas, and BEA economic areas. By metropolitan area, Austin-San Marcos, TX, had the fastest growth in personal income (10.6 percent) from 1996 to 1997, and San Francisco, CA, had the highest per capita personal income ($41,128) in 1997. These estimates incorporate the results of the most recent revision of the annual estimates of State personal income as well as new and revised county-level source data for 1995--96.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0599rem.pdf','Regional, Local area personal income','1999-05-17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-06-01',79,6,'June',1999,'Note on Rates of Return for Domestic Nonfinancial Corporations, 1960--98','Daniel Larkins',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0699cba.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-06-11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-06-02',79,6,'June',1999,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Florence H. Campi','Real GDP increased 4.1 percent in the first quarter of 1999 after increasing 6.0 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998; the price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.1 percent after increasing 0.9 percent. Corporate profits increased $31.8 billion in the first quarter. The Federal Government current surplus increased $45.6 billion, to $111.4 billion, in the first quarter, and the State and local government current surplus decreased $2.4 billion, to $168.1 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0699bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-06-11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-06-03',79,6,'June',1999,'Foreign Direct Investment in the United States: New Investment in 1998','Mahnaz Fahim-Nader','Outlays by foreign investors to acquire or establish businesses in the United States jumped to a record $201.0 billion in 1998 from $69.7 billion in 1997. The 1998 total was boosted by two exceptionally large acquisitions, but even excluding them, outlays were still considerably higher than the previous record.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/1999/0699fdi.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','1999-06-11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-06-04',79,6,'June',1999,'Gross State Product by Industry, 1995--97','Richard M. Beemiller, Michael T. Wells','In 1997, the States with the fastest growth in real gross state product (GSP) were Oregon, New Hampshire, Texas, Arizona, and Colorado; Hawaii was the only State in which real GSP declined. The new and revised GSP estimates are consistent with the most recent estimates of gross product by industry for the Nation, and they incorporate the most recent annual revisions of State personal income and of the national income and product accounts.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/GSP/1999/0699rea.pdf','Regional, Gross state product','1999-06-11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-06-05',79,6,'June',1999,'Subject Guide: Volume 79 (1999), Numbers 1--6',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/0699sg.pdf',NULL,'1999-06-11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-01',79,7,'July',1999,'U.S. International Transactions, Revised Estimates for 1982--98','Christopher L. Bach','In this year\'s annual revision of the balance of payments accounts, the structure of the accounts is modified in order to improve the presentation of the different types of international transactions and to bring the accounts into closer alignment with international guidelines. As a result, U.S. international transactions are now classified into three groups---the current account, the capital account, and the financial account. Several major improvements to the estimates are also introduced, including improved measures of income receipts and improved seasonal adjustment of exports of goods. The revised estimate of the U.S. current-account deficit for 1998 is $-220.6 billion, compared with the previously published estimate of $-233.4 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0799bpr.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-02',79,7,'July',1999,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 4.3 percent in the first quarter of 1999, according to the NIPA \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 4.1-percent increase. Corporate profits increased $47.1 billion (or 5.7 percent at a quarterly rate) in the first quarter after decreasing $5.3 billion (0.6 percent) in the fourth.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0799bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-03',79,7,'July',1999,'U.S. Multinational Companies: Operations in 1997','Raymond J. Mataloni, Jr.','The operations of U.S. multinational companies (MNC\'s) continued to grow at a strong pace in 1997: Worldwide gross product of U.S. parent companies and their majority-owned foreign affiliates increased 5.6 percent, employment increased 6.1 percent, and capital expenditures increased 13.7 percent. The strong growth in MNC operations reflected continued economic growth and a strong upturn in new investments.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/USINVEST/1999/0799mnc.pdf','International, U.S. multinational companies','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-04',79,7,'July',1999,'The International Investment Position of the United States at Yearend 1998','Russell B. Scholl','The net international investment position of the United States became more negative in 1998: On a current-cost basis, it was $-1,239.2 billion, compared with $-968.2 billion in 1997; and on a market-value basis, it was $-1,537.5 billion, compared with $-1,066.3 billion in 1997. The net position on both bases became more negative mainly as a result of large net financial inflows and strong price appreciation in foreign-owned assets in the United States that reflected a steep rise in U.S. stock prices.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0799iip.pdf','International, U.S. international investment position','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-05',79,7,'July',1999,'Direct Investment Positions for 1998: Country and Industry Detail','Sylvia E. Bargas, Rosaria Troia','In 1998, the U.S. direct investment position abroad valued at historical cost increased 13 percent, reflecting record capital outflows---mainly equity capital and reinvested earnings. By country, the largest increases were with the United Kingdom and the Netherlands. The foreign direct investment position in the United States valued at historical cost increased 17 percent, reflecting record capital inflows that were boosted by two exceptionally large transactions involving acquisitions of U.S. firms. By country, the largest increases were with Germany and the United Kingdom.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/1999/0799dip.pdf','International, Direct investment positions: Country and industry detail','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-06',79,7,'July',1999,'U.S. International Transactions, First Quarter 1999','Douglas B. Weinberg','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $6.9 billion, to $68.6 billion, in the first quarter of 1999, as a large increase in the deficit on goods more than offset a small increase in the surplus on services, a small decrease in the deficit on income, and a decrease in net unilateral current transfers. In the financial account, net recorded inflows slowed to $84.1 billion from $99.2 billion, as a sharp slowdown in inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States more than offset a shift from outflows to inflows for transactions in U.S.-owned assets abroad.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/0799bop.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-07-07',79,7,'July',1999,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/0799niw.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','1999-07-14',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-08-01',79,8,'August',1999,'A Preview of the 1999 Comprehensive Revision of the National Income and Product Accounts: Definitional and Classificational Changes','Brent R. Moulton, Robert P. Parker, Eugene P. Seskin','The upcoming comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s will feature a number of definitional and classificational changes that will significantly improve the NIPA measures of output, investment, and saving. In particular, business and government expenditures for software will be recognized as fixed investment, government employee retirement plans will be reclassified from the government sector to the personal sector, and certain transactions will be reclassified as capital transfers. The recognition of software as investment will raise GDP (for 1996, by roughly 1 percent); the other definitional and classificational changes will have little effect on GDP, but several of them will raise private saving and reduce government saving.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/national/nipa/1999/0899niw.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-08-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-08-02',79,8,'August',1999,'Foreign Direct Investment in the United States: Preliminary Results From the 1997 Benchmark Survey','William J. Zeile','In 1997, U.S. affiliates of foreign companies accounted for 6.3 percent of U.S. gross product originating in private nonbank industries and for 4.9 percent of U.S. employment. Trade by U.S. affiliates accounted for 20 percent of U.S. exports of goods and for 30 percent of U.S. imports of goods. Affiliates accounted for more than half of U.S. exports of goods to Japan and for more than half of U.S. imports from Japan, Switzerland, Germany, and Sweden. These findings are based on the preliminary results of BEA\'s 1997 Benchmark Survey of Foreign Investment in the United States. This survey marks the first use by BEA of a new industry classification system that is based on the North American Industry Classification System.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/1999/0899iid.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','1999-08-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-08-03',79,8,'August',1999,'Business Situation','Daniel Larkins, Larry R. Moran, Ralph W. Morris','Real GDP increased 2.3 percent in the second quarter of 1999 after increasing 4.3 percent in the first quarter; the slowdown was mainly accounted for by a deceleration in consumer spending and a downturn in government spending. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.1 percent after increasing 1.2 percent; the step-up reflected a sharp upturn in energy prices.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0899bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-08-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-08-04',79,8,'August',1999,'State Personal Income, First Quarter 1999','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation increased 1.2 percent in the first quarter of 1999. The States with the fastest growth were Idaho, Maine, South Carolina, Wyoming, New York, Florida, and California. Personal income declined in North Dakota, Nebraska, South Dakota, and Iowa, and it was unchanged in Delaware.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/0899spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','1999-08-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-09-01',79,9,'September',1999,'A Preview of the 1999 Comprehensive Revision of the National Income and Product Accounts: New and Redesigned Tables','Brent R. Moulton, David F. Sullivan','As part of the upcoming comprehensive revision, the presentation of the NIPA\'s will be updated to reflect the definitional, classificational, and statistical changes that will be introduced and to make the tables more informative. Seventeen new tables will be introduced, including tables that provide additional detail and supplement the existing table on contributions to percent change in real GDP, tables on changes in the net stock of produced assets and on motor vehicle output, and summary tables that highlight percent changes and contributions to percent changes in real GDP. In addition, many of the existing tables will be redesigned to reflect the definitional changes, such as the recognition of business and government expenditures on software as investment.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0999niw.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-09-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-09-02',79,9,'September',1999,'Business Situation','R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Kurt S. Bersani','Real GDP increased 1.8 percent in the second quarter of 1999, according to the \"preliminary\" estimate; the \"advance\" estimate issued last month had shown a 2.3-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 2.1 percent, the same increase that was shown in the \"advance\" estimate. Corporate profits decreased $9.2 billion (or 1.1 percent at a quarterly rate) in the second quarter. The Federal Government current surplus increased $18.1 billion, to $140.8 billion, in the second quarter, and the State and local government current surplus increased $0.5 billion, to $170.2 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/0999bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-09-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-09-03',79,9,'September',1999,'1999 Customer Satisfaction Report',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/0999cust.pdf',NULL,'1999-09-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-09-04',79,9,'September',1999,'Foreign Direct Investment in the United States: Detail for Historical-Cost Position and Related Capital and Income Flows, 1998','Jeffrey H. Lowe',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/FDINVEST/1999/0999fdi.pdf','International, Foreign direct investment in the United States','1999-09-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-09-05',79,9,'September',1999,'U.S. Direct Investment Abroad: Detail for Historical-Cost Position and Related Capital and Income Flows, 1998','Jeffrey H. Lowe',NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/USINVEST/1999/0999usd.pdf','International, U.S. direct investment abroad','1999-09-13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-01',79,10,'October',1999,'A Preview of the 1999 Comprehensive Revision of the National Income and Product Accounts: Statistical Changes','Brent R. Moulton, Eugene P. Seskin','The upcoming comprehensive revision of the NIPA\'s will feature a number of statistical changes that improve the estimates by using newly available source data or by introducing new methodologies. The major source data that will be incorporated include the 1992 benchmark input-output accounts, preliminary estimates from the 1996 annual update of these accounts, selected data from the 1997 economic censuses, and regular source data that would normally be incorporated in an annual revision of the NIPA\'s. In addition, methodological changes will be incorporated that make the income estimates more consistent with the product estimates, improve the estimates of State and local government taxes, provide a better measure of the real value of unpriced bank services, and improve the prices of a number of NIPA estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1099niw.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-02',79,10,'October',1999,'Business Situation','Ralph W. Morris, Daniel Larkins','Real GDP increased 1.6 percent in the second quarter of 1999, according to the NIPA \"final\" estimate; the \"preliminary\" estimate issued last month had shown a 1.8-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.9 percent; the \"preliminary\" estimate had shown a 2.1-percent increase. Corporate profits decreased $9.5 billion (revised), or 1.1 percent at a quarterly rate, in the second quarter after increasing $47.1 billion, or 5.7 percent, in the first quarter.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1099bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-03',79,10,'October',1999,'U.S. International Transactions, Second Quarter 1999','Douglas B. Weinberg','The U.S. current-account deficit increased $12.0 billion, to $80.7 billion, in the second quarter of 1999; most of the increase was accounted for by a large increase in the deficit on goods. In the financial account, net recorded inflows surged $43.2 billion, to $116.9 billion; partly reflecting several very large acquisitions of U.S. companies by foreign companies, inflows for foreign-owned assets in the United States increased even more strongly than outflows for U.S.-owned assets abroad.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/1099it.pdf','International, U.S. international transactions','1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-04',79,10,'October',1999,'U.S. International Services: Cross-Border Trade in 1998 and Sales Through Affiliates in 1997','Michael A. Mann, Laura L. Brokenbaugh, Sylvia E. Bargas','In 1998, U.S. cross-border exports of private services increased 2 percent to $245.7 billion, and U.S. cross-border imports of private services increased 8 percent to $165.3 billion; as a result, the U.S. surplus on cross-border trade in services decreased to $80.4 billion from $88.0 billion. In 1997, sales of services abroad by foreign affiliates of U.S. companies again substantially exceeded sales of services in the United States by U.S. affiliates of foreign companies: Sales by foreign affiliates were $258.3 billion, up 16 percent from 1996, while sales by U.S. affiliates were $205.5 billion, up 22 percent. About half of the increase in sales by U.S. affiliates was attributable to the use of new definitions of sales of services that are based on the North American Industry Classification System.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/INTSERV/1999/1099srv.pdf','International, U.S. international services','1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-05',79,10,'October',1999,'Real Inventories, Sales, and Inventory-Sales Ratios for Manufacturing and Trade',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/1099is.pdf','National, Inventories, sales, and inventory sales ratios for manufacturing and trade','1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-10-06',79,10,'October',1999,'2000 Release Dates for BEA Estimates',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/1099rd.pdf',NULL,'1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/1099rd.pdf',NULL,'1999-10-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-11-01',79,11,'November',1999,'Initial Results of the 1999 Comprehensive Revision of the National Income and Product Accounts',NULL,'On October 28, 1999, BEA released revised estimates for 1959--99 from the 11th comprehensive revision of the national income and product accounts. Comprehensive revisions, which are carried out every 4 to 5 years, are an important part of BEA\'s regular process for improving and modernizing its accounts to keep pace with the ever-changing U.S. economy. According to the revised estimates, real GDP is growing faster than previously estimated, and the rate of personal saving is higher, though still with a pronounced downtrend.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1199gdp.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-11-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-11-02',79,11,'November',1999,'Assessing BEA\'s Prototype Integrated Economic and Environmental Satellite Accounts','J. Steven Landefeld','Recently, the Panel on Integrated Environmental and Economic Accounting, a panel of experts under the aegis of the National Research Council\'s Committee on National Statistics, issued a Congressionally requested assessment of the work on environmental accounting that BEA published in April 1994. The panel concluded that BEA had produced a set of sound and objective prototype satellite accounts and that such environmental accounts, within the context of a broader set of nonmarket accounts, would add valuable information to the basic NIPA\'s.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPAREL/1999/1199od.pdf','National, Satellite accounts','1999-11-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-11-03',79,11,'November',1999,'Reconciliation of the U.S.-Canadian Current Account, 1997 and 1998','Anthony DiLullo, Hugh Henderson','For 1997, after the reconciliation, the U.S. current-account balance with Canada shows a U.S. deficit, in contrast to the U.S. surplus that is shown in the U.S.-published accounts. For 1998, the reconciled balance shows a larger U.S. deficit than is shown in the U.S.-published accounts. These annual reconciliations show how the current-account estimates would appear if both countries used the same definitions, methodologies, and data sources.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/INTERNAT/BPA/1999/1199bop.pdf','International, Reconciliation of the U.S. Canadian current account','1999-11-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-11-04',79,11,'November',1999,'State Personal Income, Second Quarter 1999','Duke Tran','Personal income in the Nation increased 1.3 percent in the second quarter of 1999, about the same pace as in the first quarter. In the second quarter, the States with the fastest growth were Nebraska, Kansas, Iowa, Nevada, and Arizona. The States with the slowest growth were New York, North Carolina, Alaska, and West Virginia.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/REGIONAL/perinc/1999/1199spi.pdf','Regional, State personal income','1999-11-12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-01',79,12,'December',1999,'Improved Estimates of the National Income and Product Accounts for 1959--98: Results of the Comprehensive Revision','Eugene P. Seskin','On October 28, 1999, BEA released revised NIPA estimates beginning with 1959 that reflected the incorporation of major definitional and statistical improvements that are designed to better measure the evolving U.S. economy. This article describes the revisions to GDP and to other major NIPA aggregates and components, and it identifies the principal sources of these revisions. For example, according to the revised estimates, real GDP grew faster than previously estimated; the faster growth rate was primarily attributable to a definitional change that recognized software as investment and to statistical changes to the price estimates.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1299niw.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-02',79,12,'December',1999,'Business Situation','Larry R. Moran, Daniel Larkins, Ralph W. Morris, Deborah Y. Sieff, Kurt S. Bersani','Real GDP increased 5.5 percent in the third quarter of 1999, according to the \"preliminary\" estimate; the \"advance\" estimate issued last month had shown a 4.8-percent increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases increased 1.7 percent, 0.1 percentage point more than the previously published increase. Corporate profits increased $8.2 billion (or 0.9 percent at a quarterly rate) in the third quarter. The Federal Government current surplus increased $16.6 billion, to $134.7 billion, in the third quarter, and the State and local government surplus increased $10.7 billion, to $48.3 billion.','http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1299bs.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-03',79,12,'December',1999,'National Income and Product Accounts Tables',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1299nipa.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-04',79,12,'December',1999,'GDP and Other Major NIPA Series, 1959--99',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/NATIONAL/NIPA/1999/1299nip2.pdf','National, National income and product accounts (NIPAs)','1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-05',79,12,'December',1999,'Subject Guide: Volume 79 (1999)',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/1299sg.pdf',NULL,'1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('SCB-79-12-06',79,12,'December',1999,'2000 Release Dates for BEA Estimates',NULL,NULL,'http://bea.gov/scb/pdf/BEAWIDE/1999/1299rd.pdf',NULL,'1999-12-15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
